The paper discusses a form of coding that reduces arithmetic precision, execution time, table sizes, and coding delay, making it faster and more space-efficient than arithmetic coding. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) or Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses compression gains and predictability of data, which are topics often discussed in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the division of labor between the coder and modeler, which is a topic that falls under the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
